<misra_rule>
MISRA C 2023 Rule 2.1 is: A project shall not contain unreachable code.

</misra_rule>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- is_rule_violated: whether the rule is violated or not (true/false),
- scenario: a specific violation scenario.
</response format>
<target_code>
Here is the code of OS_ForEachFilterCreator:
```c
bool OS_ForEachFilterCreator(void *ref, const OS_object_token_t *token, const OS_common_record_t *obj)
{
    OS_creator_filter_t *filter = ref;

    /*
     * Check if the obj_id is both valid and matches
     * the specified creator_id
     */
    return (OS_ObjectIdIsValid(obj->active_id) && (OS_ObjectIdEqual(filter->creator_id, OS_OBJECT_CREATOR_ANY) ||
                                                   OS_ObjectIdEqual(obj->creator, filter->creator_id)));
}
```
</target_code>
<additional code>Here are the definitions of symbols that are close to the target function OS_ForEachFilterCreator:
static inline bool OS_ObjectIdIsValid(osal_id_t object_id)
{
    osal_objtype_t objtype = OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl(object_id);
    return (objtype > OS_OBJECT_TYPE_UNDEFINED && objtype < OS_OBJECT_TYPE_USER);
}
...
static inline bool OS_ObjectIdEqual(osal_id_t object_id1, osal_id_t object_id2)
{
    return (OS_ObjectIdToInteger(object_id1) == OS_ObjectIdToInteger(object_id2));
}
...
#define OS_OBJECT_CREATOR_ANY OS_OBJECT_ID_UNDEFINED
...
typedef struct
{
    osal_id_t        creator_id;
    OS_ArgCallback_t user_callback;
    void *           user_arg;
} OS_creator_filter_t
...
typedef struct OS_common_record OS_common_record_t
</additional code>
<target_code>
Here is the code fragment that you need to analyze:
```c
static inline bool OS_ObjectIdIsValid(osal_id_t object_id)
{
    osal_objtype_t objtype = OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl(object_id);
    return (objtype > OS_OBJECT_TYPE_UNDEFINED && objtype < OS_OBJECT_TYPE_USER);
}
```
Focus on the above code fragment and judge whether it violates the rule 2.1 or not.
</target_code>
scenario: No unreachable code in this function. The function computes objtype and returns the result of a boolean expression; both statements can be executed and there are no code paths that can never be reached. (A hypothetical violation scenario would be if the enum/macro values were mis-defined so the comparison expression is a compile-time constant making some callers' branches unreachable — e.g. if OS_OBJECT_TYPE_USER <= OS_OBJECT_TYPE_UNDEFINED the expression would always be false and any caller branch guarded by a true result would be effectively unreachable.)
